icantly while japanese handset manufacturers retreated to become virtual nonplayers korean firms gained global prominence this paper argues that the politics of standard setting and liberalization set in motion by differences in initial conditions that created distinct domestic market dynamics are critical in explaining this divergence the korean government seeking independence from foreign equipment actively sought to build domestic technological capacities through a standard that would advantage domestic firms in international markets in contrast the japanese government independent from foreign technology was not initially focused on international markets making it difficult later on to shift the terms of market competition away from an exclusive focus on the domestic market download html+ go to site external http www tandfonline com doi abs parent research information technology in japan and asia japan studies program project topics information technology japan south korea search aparc search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages publications of interest north korea and identity politics in south korea gi wook shin kristin c burke brown journal of world affairs vol 15 1 2008 pdf+ cover aging asia the economic and social implications of rapid demographic change in china japan and south korea karen eggleston shripad tuljapurkar shorenstein aparc distributed by the brookings institution press 2010 buy+ cover china and the us japan and us korea alliances in a changing northeast asia chu shulong shorenstein aparc 1999 pdf+ the political economies of broadband development in korea and japan kenji kushida seung youn oh asian survey vol 47 3 2007 html+ cover support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 9741 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
